How can we use our solution from
{part(a)}
and the initial conditions to find the true particular solution?

sols_latex:
Recall from
{part
(a)} that we figured out that the general solution was

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y}(t)=c_1
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
2
\end{bmatrix}\exp(-t)
+ c_2
\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix}\exp(-2t).
\end{align*}

With the initial condition

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y}(0)=
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix},
\end{align*}

we can find the constants $c_1$ and $c_2$ for this particular problem.
Plugging in the initial condition we get,

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y}(0)=c_1
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
2
\end{bmatrix}\exp(0)
+ c_2
\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix}\exp(0)=
\begin{bmatrix}
c_1+2c_2\\
2c_1+3c_2
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

Therefore we conclude that,

\begin{align*}
\left\{\begin{aligned}
c_1+2c_2&=1\\
2c_1+3c_2&=1
\end{aligned}\right.
\end{align*}

which has solution, $c_1=-1$ and $c_2=1$. Therefore the solution to this
problem with initial condition

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y}(0)=
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

is

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y}(t)=-
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
2
\end{bmatrix}\exp(-t)
+ 
\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix}\exp(-2t).
\end{align*}

statement_latex:
Consider the differential equation system

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y}'=A\mathbf{y}
\end{align*}

where A has eigenvalues $\lambda_1=-1$ and $\lambda_2=-2$ with
corresponding eigenvectors

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{k}_1&=
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
2
\end{bmatrix},\qquad
\mathbf{k}_2&=
\begin{bmatrix}
2\\
3
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

Find the solution that matches the initial conditions

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{y}(0)=
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}
